 GCP Network Architecture



 1Ô∏è‚É£ VPC (Virtual Private Cloud)

 GCP private network, isolated per project
 Can span regions (global) or be regional
 Define IP range (CIDR) for subnets



 2Ô∏è‚É£ Subnets

 Public Subnet ‚Üí VM has external IP ‚Üí reachable from Internet
 Private Subnet ‚Üí VM has only internal IP ‚Üí internal traffic only



 3Ô∏è‚É£ Internet Gateway / Cloud NAT

 IGW ‚Üí Allows public subnet VMs to receive traffic from Internet
 Cloud NAT ‚Üí Private subnet VMs ‚Üí Internet outbound only (patches, updates)



 4Ô∏è‚É£ Route Tables

 GCP automatically creates default routes
 You can define custom routes for peering, VPN, or specific CIDRs



 5Ô∏è‚É£ Firewall Rules

 GCP firewall = Security Groups in AWS / NSG in Azure
 VM-level / subnet-level rules
 Stateful by default
 Example: Allow TCP 22, 80, 443



 6Ô∏è‚É£ Load Balancer

 Distributes traffic across multiple VMs
 Types:

   HTTP(S) Load Balancer ‚Üí Layer 7
   Network Load Balancer ‚Üí Layer 4



 7Ô∏è‚É£ VPN / VPC Peering

 VPC Peering ‚Üí Private connectivity between two VPCs
 Cloud VPN ‚Üí Connect on-prem or other cloud network securely
 Linux admin ensures routing, firewall, and connectivity



 8Ô∏è‚É£ DNS (Cloud DNS)

 Converts domain ‚Üí IP
 Linux admin debug using:

```bash
dig
nslookup
```



 9Ô∏è‚É£ Linux Admin Role

 Verify VPC, subnet, firewall, route tables
 Test connectivity with Linux tools (`ping`, `traceroute`, `ssh`)
 Ensure private subnet VMs can access Internet via NAT
 Troubleshoot VPN / Peering / DNS issues



```
             Internet Users
                    |
                  Cloud DNS
                    |
            -
            |  GCP Load Balancer  |
            -
              |               |
       Public Subnet      Public Subnet
       VM Web Server      VM Web Server
              |               |
              --
                     |
              Private Subnet
            App / DB Servers
                     |
                Cloud NAT
                     |
                  Internet
```





AWS vs Azure vs GCP ‚Äì Key Network Differences

| Feature                  | AWS                                                                  | Azure                                                 | GCP                                           |
| ------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| VPC / Network Name   | VPC                                                                  | VNet                                                  | VPC                                           |
| Subnet               | Subnet (public/private)                                              | Subnet (public/private)                               | Subnet (regional, public/private)             |
| IP Assignment        | Private IPs, Elastic IP (optional public)                            | Private IPs, Public IP (optional)                     | Private IPs, External IP (optional)           |
| Internet Access      | Internet Gateway (IGW)                                               | Public IP + Default Route                             | Default Internet / IGW equivalent             |
| Private Outbound     | NAT Gateway / NAT Instance                                           | NAT Gateway                                           | Cloud NAT                                     |
| Firewall             | Security Group (VM-level, stateful) / NACL (subnet-level, stateless) | NSG (VM/subnet, stateful) / Azure Firewall (optional) | Firewall Rules (VM/subnet, stateful)          |
| Load Balancer        | ALB (L7) / NLB (L4)                                                  | Application Gateway (L7) / LB (L4)                    | HTTP(S) LB (L7) / Network LB (L4)             |
| Private Connectivity | VPC Peering, VPN, Transit Gateway                                    | VNet Peering, VPN Gateway, ExpressRoute               | VPC Peering, Cloud VPN, Shared VPC            |
| DNS                  | Route 53                                                             | Azure DNS                                             | Cloud DNS                                     |
| Routing              | Route Tables (custom per subnet)                                     | Route Tables (custom per subnet)                      | Routes (per VPC, auto and custom)             |
| Key Linux Admin Role | Validate SG/NACL, route tables, LB, DNS, NAT                         | Validate NSG, route tables, LB, DNS, NAT              | Validate Firewall, route tables, LB, DNS, NAT |



 üîπ Key Conceptual Differences

1. Firewall implementation

    AWS ‚Üí SG (stateful) + NACL (stateless)
    Azure ‚Üí NSG (stateful) + optional Azure Firewall
    GCP ‚Üí Firewall Rules (stateful) only, no separate stateless NACL

2. Private subnet Internet access

    AWS ‚Üí NAT Gateway
    Azure ‚Üí NAT Gateway
    GCP ‚Üí Cloud NAT

3. Load Balancer names

    AWS ‚Üí ALB / NLB
    Azure ‚Üí App Gateway / LB
    GCP ‚Üí HTTP(S) LB / Network LB

4. Private connectivity terminology

    AWS ‚Üí VPC Peering, Transit Gateway
    Azure ‚Üí VNet Peering, ExpressRoute (for on-prem)
    GCP ‚Üí VPC Peering, Cloud VPN, Shared VPC

5. DNS service

    AWS ‚Üí Route 53
    Azure ‚Üí Azure DNS
    GCP ‚Üí Cloud DNS


